        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Play! Framework : nouvelle librairie play.libs.F]]></title>
        <link href="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/2011/05/03/play-framework-nouvelle-librairie-play.libs.f.html"/>
        <updated>2011-05-03T00:00:00+02:00</updated>
        <id>http://www.web-tambouille.fr/2011/05/03/play-framework-nouvelle-librairie-play.libs.f</id>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://picasaweb.google.com/lh/photo/g_xu25hlrSYnu-hqwUZugQ?feat=embedwebsite"><img style="float: right; margin-left: 15px; margin-bottom: 5px;" title="Play! Framework" src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-Mz7Ky8bTH_w/ThmqRGRBo3I/AAAAAAAAAuc/99jxThf7F0U/s800/logo_play.jpg" alt="Play! Framework" width="170" height="63" /></a><a href="http://www.playframework.org/" target="_blank">Play! Framework</a>, que je vous avais pr&eacute;sent&eacute; lors de la sortie de la <a href="http://web-tambouille.fr/2010/12/13/sortie-de-play-framework-1.1.html" target="_blank">version 1.1</a>,&nbsp;continue sa route avec une <a href="http://blog.xebia.fr/2011/04/19/revue-de-presse-xebia-207/#Sortiesdeplayframeworketscalap" target="_blank">nouvelle version 1.2</a>&nbsp;<em>(et m&ecirc;me <a href="http://www.playframework.org/download" target="_blank">1.2.1 depuis hier</a>)</em> qui apporte moult nouveaut&eacute;s.</p>


<p>Au menu : un syst&egrave;me de gestion de d&eacute;pendances, la gestion des&nbsp;<em>Web Sockets</em> et du <em>Long Polling</em>, un syst&egrave;me de gestion d'&eacute;volution de la base de donn&eacute;es <em>(un must que j'appr&eacute;cie d&eacute;j&agrave; !)</em>, H2 qui remplace Hsqldb ou bien encore une meilleure int&eacute;gration du&nbsp;<a href="http://scala.playframework.org/" target="_blank">langage Scala</a> <em>(qui fera l'objet d'un prochain article)</em>.</p>


<p>Mais une autre nouveaut&eacute;, peu mise en avant, a fait son apparition par une librairie. Ainsi, aux c&ocirc;t&eacute;s des tr&egrave;s connues&nbsp;<a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/1.2/libs" target="_blank">play.libs Files, Mail ou WS</a> se trouve&nbsp;<a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/1.2/libs#FunctionalprogrammingwithJava" target="_blank">play.libs.F</a> ou la librairie fonctionnelle de Play. Regardons cela de plus pr&egrave;s...</p>


<p>Au menu :</p>


<ul>
<li>Option&lt;T&gt;</li>
<li>Either&lt;A, B&gt;</li>
<li>Tuple&lt;A, B&gt;</li>
<li>Promise&lt;V&gt;</li>
<li>Pattern Matching</li>
<li>Conclusion</li>
</ul>


<p><!--more--></p>


<h3>Option&lt;T&gt;</h3>


<p>Le premier objet orient&eacute; programmation fonctionnelle que nous propose Play est l'<a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/api/1.2/play/libs/F.Option.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Option&lt;T&gt;</span></a>. Une option est un objet de type conteneur qui contiendra ou non un objet. Ses instances possibles&nbsp;<em>(<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some ou None</span>)</em> auront toutes deux des m&eacute;thodes que nous pourrons librement appeler sans nous occuper de la nullit&eacute; de l'objet wrapp&eacute;. Ainsi, tout comme en&nbsp;<a href="http://blog.danielwellman.com/2008/03/using-scalas-op.html" target="_blank">Scala</a>, l'option permet simplement d'&eacute;viter les <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">NullPointerException</span> et les tests <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">object != null</span>.</p>


<p>L'acc&egrave;s &agrave; cette classe se fait par l'objet <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">F</span> <em>(<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">F.Option</span>)</em> et ce sera d'ailleurs le cas pour toutes les autres classes. Ainsi, pour avoir un code plus lisible, je vous conseille fortement d'utiliser les imports statiques pour ne pas avoir des choses du style <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">F.Option.Some(x)</span> mais plut&ocirc;t directement <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some(x)</span>. On sait que l'on a affaire &agrave; la librairie <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">F</span> de Play donc pas besoin d'en rajouter dans tous les sens...</p>


<p>L'Option se pr&eacute;sente sous forme abstraite et poss&egrave;de 2 m&eacute;thodes nomm&eacute;es <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some(T value)</span> et <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">None()</span> qui permettent de retourner des instances concr&egrave;tes.&nbsp;<a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/api/1.2/play/libs/F.Some.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some&lt;T&gt;</span></a> sera l'instance qui contiendra un objet tandis que <a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/api/1.2/play/libs/F.None.html" target="_blank"><span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">None</span></a> sera l'instance sans objet. Le nommage est plut&ocirc;t pas mal non <img title="Laughing" src="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/tinymce/plugins/emoticons/img/smiley-laughing.gif" border="0" alt="Laughing" />. Voici quelques exemples :</p>


<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
<span class='line-number'>8</span>
<span class='line-number'>9</span>
<span class='line-number'>10</span>
<span class='line-number'>11</span>
<span class='line-number'>12</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='java'><span class='line'><span class="nd">@Test</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="kd">public</span> <span class="kt">void</span> <span class="nf">test_option_as_some</span><span class="o">()</span> <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="n">Option</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">String</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">option</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Some</span><span class="o">(&amp;</span><span class="n">ldquo</span><span class="o">;</span><span class="n">Value</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">rdquo</span><span class="o">;);</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="n">assertThat</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">option</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">isDefined</span><span class="o">(),</span> <span class="n">is</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="kc">true</span><span class="o">));</span>   <span class="n">assertThat</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">option</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">get</span><span class="o">(),</span> <span class="n">is</span><span class="o">(&amp;</span><span class="n">ldquo</span><span class="o">;</span><span class="n">Value</span><span class="o">&amp;</span><span class="n">rdquo</span><span class="o">;));</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">}&lt;/</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="o">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">p</span><span class="o">&gt;</span><span class="nd">@Test</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">expected</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">IllegalStateException</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">class</span><span class="o">)</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="kd">public</span> <span class="kt">void</span> <span class="nf">test_option_as_none</span><span class="o">()</span> <span class="o">{</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="n">Option</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">String</span><span class="o">&gt;</span> <span class="n">option</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">None</span><span class="o">();</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="n">assertThat</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="n">option</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">isDefined</span><span class="o">(),</span> <span class="n">is</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="kc">false</span><span class="o">));</span>
</span><span class='line'>   <span class="n">option</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="na">get</span><span class="o">();</span>
</span><span class='line'><span class="o">}</span>
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>On voit que le <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some</span> se passe tr&egrave;s bien avec un appel &agrave; la m&eacute;thode&nbsp;<span style="font-family: 'comic sans ms', sans-serif;">get()</span> qui renvoie la valeur incluse. Pour <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">None</span>, une tentative de <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">get()</span> renvoie une exception de type <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">IllegalStateException</span>. A noter la pr&eacute;sence d'une m&eacute;thode <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">isDefined()</span> qui permet de savoir si l'&eacute;ventuelle valeur est d&eacute;finie.</p>


<p>Pour &ecirc;tre totalement exploitable, il manque encore des m&eacute;thodes comme <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">getOrElse(T default)</span> pour pouvoir r&eacute;ellement se passer de tests de non nullit&eacute; ou de pr&eacute;sence d'objet. C'est un bon d&eacute;but mais l'<a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/api/1.2/play/libs/F.Option.html" target="_blank">option Play</a> est encore trop vide compar&eacute;e &agrave; son <a href="http://www.scala-lang.org/api/current/scala/Option.html" target="_blank">&eacute;quivalent Scala</a>.</p>


<h3>Either&lt;A, B&gt;</h3>


<p>Un peu comme l'<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Option</span>, <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;"><a href="http://www.playframework.org/documentation/api/1.2/play/libs/F.Either.html" target="_blank">Either&lt;A,B&gt;</a></span> va &ecirc;tre un conteneur d'objet. La diff&eacute;rence sera que l'instance concr&egrave;te contiendra soit l'objet A, soit l'objet B. Mais pas les 2 ! D'o&ugrave; le nom <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Either</span>&nbsp;<img title="Wink" src="http://www.web-tambouille.fr/tinymce/plugins/emoticons/img/smiley-wink.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" /></p>


<p>Si l'instance concr&egrave;te&nbsp;<span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Either&lt;A, B&gt;</span> contient l'objet A, un appel pour r&eacute;cup&eacute;rer l'objet <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">A</span> renverra une option <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">Some&lt;A&gt;</span> <em>(car elle contient la valeur)</em> alors qu'un appel pour r&eacute;cup&eacute;rer l'objet <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">B</span> renverra une option <span style="font-family: 'courier new', courier;">None </span><em>(car l'Either ne contient pas B)</em>. En action, cela donne :</p>


<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
